WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.265 --> 00:00:05.820
EVA KOR: Thank you very much
for those of you who have come.

00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:09.860
Thank you, Emily,
May, [INAUDIBLE],

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:13.930
and May's boyfriend--
what's his name?

00:00:13.930 --> 00:00:15.070
AUDIENCE: Nam.

00:00:15.070 --> 00:00:15.760
EVA KOR: Nam.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:16.260
OK.

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:23.540
All of you who helped
organize this event,

00:00:23.540 --> 00:00:25.220
I am very pleased to be here.

00:00:25.220 --> 00:00:28.385
I can tell you, before
I begin my presentation,

00:00:28.385 --> 00:00:34.380
that I probably use Google
a minimum of 10 to 20 times

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:35.070
a day.

00:00:35.070 --> 00:00:37.060
Whatever I don't
know, I go to Google.

00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:40.250
If I don't know how to spell
it, I start spelling it,

00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:42.920
Google is going to
spell it for me right.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:46.900
But I have to be close to a
computer, because my iPhone

00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:51.860
I use for writing and sending
messages-- emails, or tweets,

00:00:51.860 --> 00:00:55.785
or whatever-- but Google helps
me with all the information.

00:00:58.490 --> 00:01:01.540
I usually like to
start my presentation

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:03.720
with the following statement.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:06.060
My name is Eva Kor.

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:11.060
I am a survivor of Auschwitz, a
survivor of medical experiments

00:01:11.060 --> 00:01:16.200
conducted by Doctor Mengele,
and now that I am 81 years old,

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:20.390
I am trying to survive old age.

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:25.460
And I am finding it a bigger
challenge than I realized.

00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:32.850
I was born in a tiny village in
1934 in Transylvania, Romania.

00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:39.500
Being born in the 1930s
or '40s a Jewish child,

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:43.100
my destiny was decided
already, because Hitler already

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:46.750
was in power in 1933.

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:49.810
Our village had 100
families, all Christian,

00:01:49.810 --> 00:01:53.750
except the Mozes
family was Jewish.

00:01:53.750 --> 00:01:57.640
And from the time that I
was six years old, when

00:01:57.640 --> 00:02:02.290
the war started, and the village
was occupied by the Hungarians,

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:06.720
persecution against
Jews began immediately.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:12.930
And I learned that children can
be very mean to one another,

00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:20.080
particularly if they are taught
to do so, and rewarded for it.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:26.610
By first grade when we entered,
we were called dirty Jews,

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:31.380
and the kids beat my
twin sister, Miriam, up.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:34.760
And when we complained
to the teacher,

00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:35.940
the teachers punished us.

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:39.550
So we learned within the
first few days in school

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:42.500
that there was no help for us.

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:46.710
When we went home, I expected
my mother to march to school

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:49.090
and straighten it all out.

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:52.480
But even though she was
a wonderful human being--

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:55.860
she hugged us, kissed
us, and cried with us--

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:58.420
but said, children,
I am very sorry.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:00.670
There is nothing I can do.

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:03.530
You have to learn
that we are Jews,

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:05.810
and you have to
learn to take it.

00:03:05.810 --> 00:03:09.200
My father's attitude was
a little bit different.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:12.530
He told us since we
were going to school,

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:15.750
to be the best students in
that one room schoolhouse,

00:03:15.750 --> 00:03:17.380
and we were.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:19.590
When we got home,
he said we needed

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:23.780
to help with the work
around the big pig farm.

00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:27.080
And at night, he said
you say your prayers.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:29.730
And he was very
strict about that,

00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:32.290
because we were Orthodox Jews.

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:35.950
And he said God is going to help
us, and everything will be OK,

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:37.790
and do not worry.

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:41.040
And, of course, I believed
it, but as time went on,

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:42.760
things changed.

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:45.920
Every six months or
so, new rules, new laws

00:03:45.920 --> 00:03:48.110
were passed against us.

00:03:48.110 --> 00:03:52.790
And in 1942, when I
was eight years old,

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:56.240
is that new laws that year
were that Jews could not

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:59.560
hire anybody but Jewish people.

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:03.230
And in our Christian village,
that was not possible.

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:05.770
My mother got sick.

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:07.430
We tried to help--
the four girls--

00:04:07.430 --> 00:04:12.110
but we couldn't handle all the
work on an old fashioned farm.

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:16.500
My father asked for a permit
to travel to the big city

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:20.380
to try to hire a Jewish
lady, but that was denied.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.880
So here I was eight years old,
and our life was very, very

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:28.410
difficult. And so
I told my father,

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:30.520
daddy, I think time
has come that we

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.770
should escape to Romania.

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:37.210
The Romanian border was just
one hour by foot from our house,

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:40.530
and the rumor was that
life for Jews in Romania

00:04:40.530 --> 00:04:42.490
was much better.

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:45.320
And it turned out
it was correct.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:48.465
Romania refused to let
Germany pick up the Jews.

00:04:48.465 --> 00:04:51.820
They said, oh, we will take care
of them in our ghettos here,

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:53.910
but you cannot take them away.

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:57.470
So all of the Jews
of Romania survived.

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.435
But my father said
to me, you are just

00:04:59.435 --> 00:05:01.150
a little girl, eight years old.

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:06.890
What on earth do you understand
about the big issues in life?

00:05:06.890 --> 00:05:13.580
I have a theory that children
between the ages of six and 13,

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:18.610
or 12, are a lot smarter than
parents give them credit.

00:05:18.610 --> 00:05:22.180
After 13, the
hormones set in, and I

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.360
don't know what happens to
all of these smart, wonderful

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:26.110
children.

00:05:26.110 --> 00:05:29.360
But I can explain it to you why.

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:34.970
Children between six and
12 function by instinct.

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:38.090
They do not
rationalize everything

00:05:38.090 --> 00:05:42.120
that's going around-- do not
try to figure it out rationally.

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:46.540
And I could sense it in
every ounce of my being

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:49.790
that things were
getting very bad.

00:05:49.790 --> 00:05:52.630
But my father said to me,
you are just a little girl.

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:53.880
You don't understand it.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.050
We have a nice home.

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:56.790
We have plenty of food.

00:05:56.790 --> 00:05:58.340
You children go to school.

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:00.880
And then he
rationalized, I think,

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:02.450
and the Nazis won't come.

00:06:02.450 --> 00:06:06.750
The Germans won't come
to this tiny village

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:09.295
to pick up six Jews.

00:06:09.295 --> 00:06:15.500
Well, daddy, I am eternally
sorry that you were 100% wrong,

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:19.780
and I, as a eight-year-old
kid, was 100% right.

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:22.560
I sure wish it was
the other way around.

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:28.980
So in March of 1944, we were
taken to a regional ghetto.

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:32.740
Two and a half months
later-- last week of May--

00:06:32.740 --> 00:06:37.670
we were herded into cattle cars,
traveling for about four days

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:40.670
without food, without water.

00:06:40.670 --> 00:06:43.650
It was very hot in
those cattle cars.

00:06:43.650 --> 00:06:45.790
And we arrived in Auschwitz.

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:48.220
Of course, we didn't know
where we were being taken.

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:54.590
The cattle car doors opened.

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:59.380
Thousands of people poured out
onto a little strip of land

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:03.560
called the selection platform.

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:07.690
In my opinion, there
is no other strip

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:11.780
of land like the selection
platform-- measuring

00:07:11.780 --> 00:07:15.270
85 feet long by 35
feet wide-- that

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:19.310
witnessed as many millions
of people being ripped apart

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:22.760
from their families forever.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:26.530
So as we were standing there,
my mother grabbed my twin sister

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:27.470
and me by the hand.

00:07:27.470 --> 00:07:30.040
We were her youngest
children, and she

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:34.480
hoped that as long as she could
hold onto us, that somehow

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:36.240
she could protect us.

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:39.800
Everything was moving very fast.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:43.640
And I-- my childish
curiosity-- I looked around,

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:46.520
trying to figure
out what on earth

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:50.670
is this place, when I realized
that my father and two older

00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:53.910
sisters disappeared
in the crowd.

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:56.500
Never ever did I see them again.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:59.220
As we were holding onto
Mother for dear life,

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:03.540
a Nazi was running, yelling
in German, twins, twins.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:06.360
We did not volunteer
any information.

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:07.840
He noticed us.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.700
Miriam and I looked alike,
and we were dressed alike,

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:14.790
and he demanded to know from
my mother if we were twins.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.190
And my mother didn't
know what to say.

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:18.970
She asked, is that good?

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:21.730
And the Nazi nodded yes,
and my mother said yes.

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:26.410
At that moment, we were
pulled in one direction,

00:08:26.410 --> 00:08:29.710
my mother was pulled in
the opposite direction.

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:32.730
We were crying, she was crying.

00:08:32.730 --> 00:08:35.600
And that was the
last time I saw her.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:38.694
I didn't even understand
that that would happen,

00:08:38.694 --> 00:08:42.850
because I might have done
something to run back

00:08:42.850 --> 00:08:45.640
to my mother and say goodbye.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:49.410
We became part of a group
of little girls, all twins.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:53.620
In our group, there were
13 sets of little girls

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:56.730
between the ages of two and 16.

00:08:56.730 --> 00:09:01.540
And one mother, who had
seven-year-old twins-- and she

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:02.810
was my mother's friend.

00:09:02.810 --> 00:09:04.975
Her name was Mrs. [? Jangary ?].

00:09:04.975 --> 00:09:09.360
We were taken to a big
building for processing,

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:11.590
which took the whole
day-- basically,

00:09:11.590 --> 00:09:15.540
sitting naked, and not knowing
what would happen to us.

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:17.960
Finally the processing began.

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:20.550
We were given short haircuts.

00:09:20.550 --> 00:09:25.840
Our dresses were returned with
a huge red cross on the back,

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:30.100
and we were tattooed
by heating a needle

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:31.780
over the flame of a lamp.

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:35.500
And when the needle got hot,
they dipped it into ink,

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:38.520
and they burned
into my left arm,

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:44.450
dot by dot, the
capital letter A-7063.

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:49.160
Miriam became capital A-7064.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:53.620
Auschwitz was the only Nazi
camp that tattooed its inmates.

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:57.380
My husband is a survivor of
four years in Buchenwald.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:00.540
He does not have a tattoo.

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:04.420
Once we were processed, we
were taken to our barrack.

00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:10.550
Crude and filthy
modular horse barns.

00:10:10.550 --> 00:10:12.570
There were no windows.

00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:16.760
We were given bunk beds on
the bottom that were covered

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:19.240
with a thin straw mattress.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:22.750
And we finally thought, after
four days in the cattle car,

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:26.120
that we could stretch
out and maybe sleep.

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:31.380
But human beings cannot function
after such a traumatic day.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.920
So I kept tossing and
turning, and as I did,

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:37.480
I noticed something big and
dark moving on the floor.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:41.260
And I counted them, and when I
got to five, I said to myself,

00:10:41.260 --> 00:10:44.780
these are the biggest mice
I have ever seen, and began

00:10:44.780 --> 00:10:47.190
screaming, "Mice."

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:50.600
A girl from the top bunk said,
silly kid, these are not mice,

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:52.210
they are rats.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:54.670
You better get used to them,
because they are everywhere.

00:10:54.670 --> 00:10:56.390
And they were.

00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:59.940
So now I couldn't even
try to go back to sleep.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:01.190
I went to the latrine.

00:11:01.190 --> 00:11:04.560
And as I entered
the place, there

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:08.580
on the filthy latrine floor
were the scattered corpses

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:10.650
of three children.

00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:15.430
I have never ever seen
anybody dead before.

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:20.060
But the message to me was
clear that in this place,

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:22.430
children were dying.

00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:26.560
So right then and there
I made a silent pledge,

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:30.480
that I will do anything and
everything within my power

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:34.180
to make sure that Miriam
and I shall not end up

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:35.930
on that filthy latrine floor.

00:11:35.930 --> 00:11:40.145
That we will somehow survive,
and walk out of this camp

00:11:40.145 --> 00:11:41.580
alive.

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:44.620
And I even had an
image in my mind

00:11:44.620 --> 00:11:49.120
of how Miriam and I might
look when we walked out

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:50.030
of this camp alive.

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:56.600
Our daily routine-- we would
be awakened every morning

00:11:56.600 --> 00:11:57.640
at 5:00 AM.

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:00.670
By 6:00 AM we were
outside for roll call.

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:02.430
And I can tell you
that by the time

00:12:02.430 --> 00:12:07.880
it was winter of 1944,
'45, [INAUDIBLE],

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:11.960
my dress was filled with
holes, and so were my shoes.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:14.930
We did not get any
winter clothes.

00:12:14.930 --> 00:12:17.180
I have no idea how
we survived it.

00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:25.020
Just for the sake of getting
through my lecture faster,

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:29.570
I will just give you a
description of our experience

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:30.480
in the barrack.

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:33.830
We were mostly little girls.

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:38.520
At one time 200,
300, 400, depending

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:41.120
on how many [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:46.060
We were little girls between
the age of two and 16,

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:52.105
huddled in our filthy bunk beds,
crawling with lice and rats.

00:12:52.105 --> 00:12:54.910
We were starved for food.

00:12:54.910 --> 00:12:58.640
We were starved
for human kindness.

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:01.820
And we were starved for
the love of the mothers

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:04.300
and fathers we once had.

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:09.620
We had no rights, but we
had a fierce determination

00:13:09.620 --> 00:13:11.450
to live one more day.

00:13:11.450 --> 00:13:14.770
To survive one more experiment.

00:13:14.770 --> 00:13:18.870
The experiments were
run six days a week,

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:22.780
and I was used in two
types of experiments.

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:25.230
Three days a week, we
would be placed naked

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:27.750
in a room for up to eight hours.

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:31.320
And they would measure just
about every part of my body,

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:33.210
and compare it to
my twin sister,

00:13:33.210 --> 00:13:35.690
and compare it to charts.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:40.310
These were not dangerous,
but even in Auschwitz I

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:43.010
had difficulty
coping with the fact

00:13:43.010 --> 00:13:47.530
that I was reduced to the lowest
form of humanity in existence,

00:13:47.530 --> 00:13:50.606
just a mass of breathing cells.

00:13:50.606 --> 00:13:54.400
On alternate days-- on Tuesday,
Thursday, and Saturday--

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:58.360
we would be taken to another
lab that I call the blood lab.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:01.120
There they would
tie both of my arms

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:04.440
to restrict the blood
flow, take a lot of blood

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:08.330
from my left arm, and give me
a minimum of five injections

00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:10.180
into my right arm.

00:14:10.180 --> 00:14:12.910
Those were the deadly ones.

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:18.730
The rumor was, in Auschwitz,
that these contained

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:22.660
drugs, diseases, and germs.

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:25.460
And that is probably a
pretty good assumption.

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:29.350
But we do not know
up to today what

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:31.960
was the content of
those injections,

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:35.160
nor what was the scope
of the experiments.

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:38.682
After one of those
injections I became very ill

00:14:38.682 --> 00:14:44.380
with a very high fever, a fact
I desperately tried to hide.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:47.070
My next visit to the
blood lab, instead

00:14:47.070 --> 00:14:50.880
of tying my arms for blood
taking and injections,

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:54.240
they measured my fever, and
I knew I was in trouble.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:56.140
I had a very high fever.

00:14:56.140 --> 00:15:00.670
I was trembling
in the August sun.

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:04.200
My arms and legs were very
swollen, and very painful,

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:09.340
and I had huge red spots
throughout my body.

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.690
The hospital was
another barrack,

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:16.590
but filled with people who
looked more dead than alive.

00:15:16.590 --> 00:15:20.430
Next morning, Mengele came
in with four other doctors.

00:15:20.430 --> 00:15:22.660
He never ever examined me.

00:15:22.660 --> 00:15:25.000
Just looked at my fever
chart, and then he

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.400
declared, laughing
sarcastically, saying,

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:32.160
too bad, she's so young, she
has only two weeks to live.

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:36.500
I knew he was right,
but I refused to die.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:39.900
So I made a second
silent pledge that I

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:41.390
will prove Mengele wrong.

00:15:41.390 --> 00:15:45.850
I will survive, and be
reunited with my twin sister.

00:15:45.850 --> 00:15:50.410
For the following two weeks,
I have only one clear memory.

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:53.330
I remember crawling
on the barrack floor,

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:55.530
because I no longer could walk.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:59.330
And I was crawling to reach the
other end of the barrack, where

00:15:59.330 --> 00:16:04.140
there was one faucet with water,
because this barrack was not

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:06.190
even allocated water.

00:16:06.190 --> 00:16:08.600
People were brought
there to die.

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:11.920
And as I was crawling,
I would fade in and out

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:16.400
of consciousness, and I
kept telling myself-- even

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:21.930
in a semiconscious state
of mind-- I must survive.

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:23.500
I must survive.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:27.400
After two weeks, my fever
broke, and I immediately

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:30.390
felt a lot stronger
and a lot better.

00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:34.420
It took me another three weeks
before my fever chart showed

00:16:34.420 --> 00:16:39.360
normal, and, amazingly, I
was released and reunited

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:42.680
with my twin sister,
and the other twins.

00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:48.120
But Miriam looked very sick,
and I could not understand that.

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:55.290
In Auschwitz, as I often
say, dying was very easy.

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:57.960
All around us was deaths.

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:01.600
Surviving was a full time job.

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:06.170
And the way that became
dangerous-- the dangerous sign

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:13.540
was-- if somebody would sit
and stare into space aimlessly,

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:16.880
that was a sign that
they have given up

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:18.650
their struggle,
because everybody

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:21.380
struggled to live one more day.

00:17:21.380 --> 00:17:23.720
And that is the
way Miriam looked,

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:25.190
and I was very surprised.

00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:27.700
And I said, what on
earth happened to you

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:30.070
in the five weeks that
I was in the hospital?

00:17:30.070 --> 00:17:32.460
She said, I cannot
talk about it.

00:17:32.460 --> 00:17:34.470
I will not talk about it.

00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:39.620
And Miriam and I never talked
about Auschwitz until 1985.

00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:43.550
The word Auschwitz never
came up in our conversation.

00:17:43.550 --> 00:17:50.970
And my opinion is that children
who struggle for their life,

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:55.020
they cannot go back
to the experience,

00:17:55.020 --> 00:18:00.570
because they have to feel
safe even as grownups.

00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:04.990
And that feeling of
safety is very important,

00:18:04.990 --> 00:18:07.480
and it's very
difficult to come by,

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:11.620
if their safety was
violated as children.

00:18:11.620 --> 00:18:16.690
And second thing is that
most survivors of atrocities

00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:20.520
are afraid if they talk about
it, they will fall apart.

00:18:20.520 --> 00:18:24.740
My experience has been
that I have only remembered

00:18:24.740 --> 00:18:27.400
as much as I could cope with.

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:31.520
So I said to Miriam, when
we talked about it in 1985,

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:35.160
I said, do you remember when
I was taken to the hospital?

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:36.720
She said, yes.

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:40.320
I said, what happened to you
while I was in the hospital?

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:44.430
Because there are no books
written about our experiments.

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:47.270
She said, well, for
the first two weeks,

00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:51.560
I was kept in isolation, and
they were waiting for something

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:53.080
to happen.

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:55.710
I don't know what that was,
because they didn't tell me.

00:18:55.710 --> 00:18:58.880
And I don't know if it
happened, or it didn't happen.

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:02.880
But it was the same two weeks
that Mengele said I would die.

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:06.390
I told Miriam, I
spoiled the experiment.

00:19:06.390 --> 00:19:08.640
I survived.

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:10.840
Would I have died,
Miriam would have

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.675
been rushed to Mengele's
lab, killed with an injection

00:19:13.675 --> 00:19:16.390
to the heart, and then
Mengele would have

00:19:16.390 --> 00:19:18.780
done the comparative autopsies.

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:22.920
That information comes to me
from the Auschwitz Museum,

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.560
where they also
told me that Mengele

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:32.540
used 1,500 sets of twins-- 3,000
individuals in the experiments.

00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:36.490
The estimated number of
survivors is 250 individuals.

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:40.800
Then I asked her
what happened to her

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.230
after the two weeks were up.

00:19:42.230 --> 00:19:46.180
She said she was injected
with many injections that

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:48.386
made her feel very sick.

00:19:48.386 --> 00:19:54.480
After the war, Miriam was always
weaker and sicker than I was.

00:19:54.480 --> 00:19:58.070
She got married
in 1958 in Israel.

00:19:58.070 --> 00:20:00.950
Expected her first
baby in 1960, and she

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:04.260
developed severe kidney
infections that did not

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:06.780
respond to any antibiotic.

00:20:06.780 --> 00:20:10.290
Second pregnancy
in '63 got worse,

00:20:10.290 --> 00:20:13.180
and this time the Israeli
doctors studied her,

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:16.000
and they found out that
Miriam's kidneys never

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:21.290
grew larger than the size
of a 10-year-old child.

00:20:21.290 --> 00:20:24.670
I begged Miriam not to
have any more children.

00:20:24.670 --> 00:20:27.760
And I said, you have two
children, that's pretty good.

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:31.430
But she had a third one, and
after her third child was born,

00:20:31.430 --> 00:20:33.240
her kidneys were deteriorating.

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:39.080
And by 1987 she needed
to go on dialysis,

00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:41.180
or have a kidney transplant.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:43.930
Well, she didn't want
to live on dialysis.

00:20:43.930 --> 00:20:45.320
I had a simple choice.

00:20:45.320 --> 00:20:47.680
I had two kidneys, one sister.

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:50.550
Of course I donated
one of my kidneys,

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:52.870
and we were a perfect match.

00:20:52.870 --> 00:20:55.870
At that hospital
near Tel Aviv, they

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:59.170
had been doing kidney
transplants for 10 years,

00:20:59.170 --> 00:21:06.050
and they had 200
survivors-- 2,000 survivors.

00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:11.000
And all of them were given
anti-rejection medication.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.610
None of them developed
cancerous polyps like Miriam

00:21:14.610 --> 00:21:17.140
did a year after the transplant.

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:19.830
And the doctors told
me that I should

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:23.070
try to find our files from
Auschwitz, because there

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:26.770
had to be something in
her body that was injected

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:30.630
in the camp that combined with
the anti-rejection medication

00:21:30.630 --> 00:21:32.730
to create the cancer.

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:35.100
We never found our files.

00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:42.010
Miriam's cancer metastasized,
and she died June 6, 1993.

00:21:42.010 --> 00:21:43.660
I will take you
back to the camp,

00:21:43.660 --> 00:21:46.490
because it's important
for me to describe

00:21:46.490 --> 00:21:52.040
to you my state of mind as
a 10-year-old in Auschwitz.

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:57.910
I thought that the whole world
was one big concentration camp.

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:00.380
That everybody is
the world lived

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:03.230
like I lived, in
miserable conditions,

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:06.080
without famillies,
starving to death,

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:09.080
and guarded by
guards day and night.

00:22:09.080 --> 00:22:13.430
Until end of August,
there was an airplane

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:15.270
that appeared over the
skies of Auschwitz.

00:22:15.270 --> 00:22:21.320
It was flying really low, and
I could see the American flag

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:23.550
on one of the wings.

00:22:23.550 --> 00:22:28.930
That gave me hope that
somebody was trying to free us.

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:33.656
And hope in Auschwitz
was in very short supply.

00:22:33.656 --> 00:22:37.000
The air raids continued
and increased.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.840
And by November of 1944,
it felt like a full fledged

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:47.100
battlefield-- continuous
air raids, artillery,

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:48.535
all the experiments stopped.

00:22:48.535 --> 00:22:52.580
Anyways, the children
developed a daily slogan

00:22:52.580 --> 00:22:56.810
that someday soon we will be
free, and we will go home.

00:22:56.810 --> 00:23:02.160
Except we had no idea
how that would happen.

00:23:02.160 --> 00:23:05.610
In early January,
the Nazis told us,

00:23:05.610 --> 00:23:07.395
everybody out of the barracks.

00:23:07.395 --> 00:23:09.920
We are taking you
deep into Germany

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:12.380
to protect you
from the fighting.

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:15.340
In my childish mind, I
didn't like the Nazi guards

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:18.260
when they were winning
the war, so I really

00:23:18.260 --> 00:23:21.030
didn't want to be near them
when they were losing it,

00:23:21.030 --> 00:23:24.370
and we decided to
stay in the barrack.

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:27.550
And I think-- as I
talked a few months ago--

00:23:27.550 --> 00:23:30.890
a few years ago to
a survivor-- I said,

00:23:30.890 --> 00:23:33.370
why did you go out
on the death marches?

00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:37.590
And they came in with their
guns, and pointed at our heads.

00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:40.220
Well, no one came
in to our barracks,

00:23:40.220 --> 00:23:43.890
so I guess I had
a guardian angel.

00:23:43.890 --> 00:23:47.630
Next morning we woke up,
opened the barrack doors.

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:49.730
All the Nazis were gone.

00:23:49.730 --> 00:23:55.020
We were on our
own-- about 8,500,

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:58.280
according to the
Auschwitz Museum.

00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:04.730
And then the Nazis came
back on January 18, 1945,

00:24:04.730 --> 00:24:10.360
to march us to Auschwitz,
and try to eliminate as much

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:13.820
of the evidence as they could.

00:24:13.820 --> 00:24:20.350
What I learned that they were
also killing without any rhyme

00:24:20.350 --> 00:24:24.410
or reason, because there
was a group of us-- 200

00:24:24.410 --> 00:24:28.440
in the kitchen-- and
when we went outside,

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:32.350
the machine guns
were just killing

00:24:32.350 --> 00:24:33.995
without any rhyme or reason.

00:24:33.995 --> 00:24:37.530
And what I remember
was a barrel of the gun

00:24:37.530 --> 00:24:39.320
about three feet from my head.

00:24:39.320 --> 00:24:42.730
And I think that when I
woke up, I looked around

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:45.450
and I was surrounded
by dead bodies.

00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:47.250
And when I reached
out and touched

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:50.305
one of the girls next
to me, she was ice cold.

00:24:50.305 --> 00:24:54.120
And this is when I realized
that I was still alive.

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:58.250
They marched us from
Birkenau Auschwitz II

00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:01.550
to Auschwitz I in the
middle of the night.

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:06.260
When we arrived there, the Nazis
were not willing to give up,

00:25:06.260 --> 00:25:09.530
and the Allies were right
outside the city limits,

00:25:09.530 --> 00:25:12.350
so they couldn't
take us any further.

00:25:12.350 --> 00:25:15.270
Heavy fighting was raging
for the next nine days.

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:18.200
My biggest problem in
Auschwitz I was there

00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:20.000
was nothing to drink.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.220
And we were very
smart survivors.

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:24.520
There was no snow on the ground.

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:28.350
We would have melted the
snow and boiled the water.

00:25:28.350 --> 00:25:32.670
So in sheer despair one day,
I went to the nearby river.

00:25:32.670 --> 00:25:36.580
I broke the ice, lowering a
container tied to a string,

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:39.750
and when I looked up,
I saw a little girl

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:43.310
with braided hair, dressed
in beautiful, clean clothes,

00:25:43.310 --> 00:25:45.450
and she was carrying
a school bag.

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:48.750
That was my first
realization that there

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:51.390
was a world beyond
the camp where

00:25:51.390 --> 00:25:56.290
children looked like
children, and went to school.

00:25:56.290 --> 00:25:58.560
A few days later,
it was very quiet.

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:00.480
Eerily quiet.

00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:05.450
I thought, well, maybe this
will be the day we will be free.

00:26:05.450 --> 00:26:07.125
We didn't know how.

00:26:07.125 --> 00:26:12.550
It was late in the afternoon
of January 27, 1945.

00:26:12.550 --> 00:26:15.180
A woman ran into
the barrack yelling

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:18.150
at the top of her
voice, "We are free.

00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:19.582
We are free.

00:26:19.582 --> 00:26:21.910
We are free."

00:26:21.910 --> 00:26:25.862
It was a wonderful
event to hear,

00:26:25.862 --> 00:26:27.570
but I didn't know
whether or not she knew

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:29.290
what she was talking about.

00:26:29.290 --> 00:26:31.850
Because when I looked down
from the second story,

00:26:31.850 --> 00:26:33.990
I couldn't see anything.

00:26:33.990 --> 00:26:36.970
I said, does she really
know what she is saying?

00:26:36.970 --> 00:26:39.650
So we went downstairs.

00:26:39.650 --> 00:26:43.830
It was snowing heavily,
and it took me 30 minutes

00:26:43.830 --> 00:26:48.775
to get my eyes and vision
adjusted to the falling snow.

00:26:48.775 --> 00:26:53.220
Where at a distance I
could see lots of people.

00:26:53.220 --> 00:26:57.220
They were all wrapped in
white camouflage raincoats.

00:26:57.220 --> 00:27:00.300
They were smiling
from ear to ear.

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:02.150
And the most important
thing, for me,

00:27:02.150 --> 00:27:05.020
was that they didn't
look like the Nazis.

00:27:05.020 --> 00:27:06.550
So we ran up to them.

00:27:06.550 --> 00:27:09.990
They gave us chocolate,
cookie, and hugs.

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:12.390
And this was my first
taste of freedom.

00:27:12.390 --> 00:27:16.610
For me to realize that
Miriam and I were alive.

00:27:16.610 --> 00:27:22.230
That my little promise to myself
that first night in the latrine

00:27:22.230 --> 00:27:24.230
became a reality.

00:27:24.230 --> 00:27:28.330
And that was an
unbelievable experience.

00:27:28.330 --> 00:27:33.230
I want to say thank you
all for listening to me.

00:27:33.230 --> 00:27:40.470
And today's lecture
is 134 this year.

00:27:40.470 --> 00:27:42.210
Which means,
basically, the reason

00:27:42.210 --> 00:27:44.740
I'm telling you
that I talk a lot.

00:27:44.740 --> 00:27:45.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:45.820 --> 00:27:48.260
And why do I talk so much?

00:27:48.260 --> 00:27:52.030
Because I have learned some very
important lessons in my life

00:27:52.030 --> 00:27:54.310
that I call them
life lessons, and I

00:27:54.310 --> 00:27:56.110
want to share them with you.

00:27:56.110 --> 00:27:58.430
Life lesson number one.

00:27:58.430 --> 00:28:02.720
Never ever give up on
yourself, or on your dreams.

00:28:02.720 --> 00:28:06.430
If you give up,
nothing will happen.

00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:10.560
And as I look at many
of your young faces,

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:16.490
I realize I remember
growing up is very hard.

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:21.580
And it's very hard even if
you live in the United States,

00:28:21.580 --> 00:28:24.130
and even if you
have loving parents.

00:28:24.130 --> 00:28:26.520
And what a thought that is.

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:29.450
That every child
in the world would

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:31.440
be born to loving parents.

00:28:31.440 --> 00:28:33.470
Wouldn't that be wonderful?

00:28:33.470 --> 00:28:36.800
And even if your loving
parents have enough money

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:40.550
to buy you jeans
with holes in them--

00:28:40.550 --> 00:28:42.360
I don't know why
that is so important,

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:49.190
but I know it's more expensive--
and even if they can buy you

00:28:49.190 --> 00:28:52.740
all the modern
gadgets, even then,

00:28:52.740 --> 00:28:56.510
every single one if you
wonders how on earth

00:28:56.510 --> 00:29:00.680
do I fit into this big,
big mixed up world.

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:05.630
Will I be able to accomplish
in life what I set out to do?

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:09.600
And I can tell you that
if you keep hammering away

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:12.710
at your wonderful
minds-- and you

00:29:12.710 --> 00:29:18.460
have lots of wonderful minds
working here at Google--

00:29:18.460 --> 00:29:19.870
will give you an answer.

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:23.880
I had no idea how to
survive Auschwitz.

00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:30.050
And here I am 70 years later,
very happy that I am alive.

00:29:30.050 --> 00:29:33.890
Life lesson number two
deals with prejudice.

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:37.460
One of the reasons that
Adolf Hitler and the Nazis

00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:40.780
rose to power, it
was a bad economy.

00:29:40.780 --> 00:29:43.870
And once Hitler convinced
his fellow Germans

00:29:43.870 --> 00:29:48.340
to vote for him-- and he
had only 1/3 of the vote,

00:29:48.340 --> 00:29:53.450
but somehow he became
chancellor of Germany.

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:57.510
Instead of taking care
of the economic problems,

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:02.270
he decided it would be a lot
faster to blame it on somebody,

00:30:02.270 --> 00:30:08.720
and Jews were always a good
group of people to blame it on.

00:30:08.720 --> 00:30:12.790
And many of the Germans
accepted the fact,

00:30:12.790 --> 00:30:17.100
because for centuries--
generations--

00:30:17.100 --> 00:30:21.410
Jews were always used as
the scapegoats for all

00:30:21.410 --> 00:30:23.330
the problems in the world.

00:30:23.330 --> 00:30:25.580
And they are used again.

00:30:25.580 --> 00:30:30.590
Just yesterday I got on Twitter
a piece of information that

00:30:30.590 --> 00:30:35.260
Angela Merkel asked
many Jews in Germany--

00:30:35.260 --> 00:30:40.140
as Rosh Hashanah and the high
holy days are approaching--

00:30:40.140 --> 00:30:43.030
not to go to the synagogue,
because they might be

00:30:43.030 --> 00:30:47.290
firebombed, and they
cannot protect them all.

00:30:47.290 --> 00:30:51.730
So in 70 years, I don't
see how much has changed.

00:30:51.730 --> 00:30:57.390
And in many countries in
Europe that is a problem.

00:30:57.390 --> 00:31:03.340
Prejudice-- I call prejudice
a cancer of the human soul.

00:31:03.340 --> 00:31:05.980
It destroys the people
who practice it,

00:31:05.980 --> 00:31:10.090
